Question 2

Swap Rates

Suppose a 6-year swap with a notional principal of $10 million is being

configured. What is the fixed rate of interest that will make the value

of the swap equal to zero. (You should use the term structure of interest rates from Question 1.)

Please submit your answer as a percentage rounded to two decimal places. So for example, if your answer is 4.567%4.567\%4.567% or equivalently 0.045670.045670.04567, then you should submit an answer of 4.574.574.57.
1 / 1 point
8.62
Correct

The discount rates are:
d(0,1)d(0,1)d(0,1) 	d(0,2)d(0,2)d(0,2) 	d(0,3)d(0,3)d(0,3) 	d(0,4)d(0,4)d(0,4) 	d(0,5)d(0,5)d(0,5) 	d(0,6)d(0,6)d(0,6)
0.93460.93460.9346 	0.86860.86860.8686 	0.80050.80050.8005 	0.73230.73230.7323 	0.66810.66810.6681 	0.60290.60290.6029

The value of the fixed interest rate, typically called the swap rate, is

given by the formula

r=1−d(0,6)∑t=16d(0,t)=0.0862=8.62% r = \frac{1-d(0,6)}{\sum_{t=1}^6 d(0,t)} = 0.0862 = 8.62\% r=∑t=16​d(0,t)1−d(0,6)​=0.0862=8.62%
