Question 3

Hedging using futures

Suppose a farmer is expecting that her crop of oranges will be ready for

harvest and sale as 150,000150,000150,000 pounds of orange juice in 333

months time. Suppose each orange juice futures contract is for 15,00015,00015,000

pounds of orange juice, and the current futures price is F0=118.65F_0 = 118.65F0​=118.65 cents-per-pound.

Assuming that the farmer has enough cash liquidity to fund

any margin calls, what is the risk-free price that she can guarantee herself.

Please submit your answer in cents-per-pound rounded to two decimal places. So for example, if your answer is 123.456123.456123.456, then you should submit an answer of 123.47123.47123.47.
1 / 1 point
118.65
Correct

She can go short 101010 futures contracts each for 15,00015,00015,000 pounds. This way

she can ensure that the payoff from the futures contract would remove

all the uncertainty in the spot price of orange juice, and she can lock

the price to 118.65118.65118.65 cents-per-pound.
