Question 4

Minimum variance hedge

Suppose a farmer is expecting that her crop of grapefruit will be ready for

harvest and sale as 150,000150,000150,000 pounds of grapefruit juice in 333

months time. She would like to use futures to hedge her risk but unfortunately there

are no futures contracts on grapefruit juice. Instead she will use orange juice futures.

Suppose each orange juice futures contract is for 15,00015,00015,000

pounds of orange juice and the current futures price is F0=118.65F_0 = 118.65F0​=118.65 cents-per-pound.

The volatility, i.e. the standard deviation, of the prices of

orange juice and grape fruit juice is 20%20\%20% and 25%25\%25%, respectively,

and the correlation coefficient is 0.70.70.7. What is the approximate number

of contracts she should purchase to minimize the variance of her payoff?

Please submit your answer rounded to the nearest integer. So for example, if your calculations result in 10.78 contracts you should submit an answer of 11.
1 / 1 point
9
Correct

Suppose the farmer goes short hhh orange juice contracts. Then the

payoff from the contract and the sale of the grape fruit juice would

be C=150,000STG−15,000h(STO−FtO)C = 150,000 S^{G}_T - 15,000 h (S^O_T - F^O_t)C=150,000STG​−15,000h(STO​−FtO​) where STGS^G_TSTG​ and

STOS^O_TSTO​ denote the price of grapefruit juice and orange juice at

expiration, and FtOF^{O}_tFtO​ denotes the current price of orange juice

futures.

Using the formula in the module slides, the minimum-variance hedge

is given by

h∗=150,00015,000⋅cov(StG,StO)var(StG)=10⋅ρσGσO=10⋅(0.7)(0.25)0.20=8.75 h^\ast = \frac{150,000}{15,000} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{cov}(S^{G}_t, S^{O}_t)}{\mathbf{var}(S^{G}_t)} = 10 \cdot \frac{\rho \sigma_G}{\sigma_O} = 10 \cdot \frac{(0.7)(0.25)}{0.20} = 8.75 h∗=15,000150,000​⋅var(StG​)cov(StG​,StO​)​=10⋅σO​ρσG​​=10⋅0.20(0.7)(0.25)​=8.75

Since the solution h∗h^\asth∗ has to be an integer, the number is

either 888 or 999.
